ucated and independent women capable of making "right" choices. The consequence of this collective investment is a feminist conundrum: agency does not denote the right to choose, but the duty to make the "right" choice; hence agency is experienced not as a sense of "freedom," but rather as a burden of responsibility.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aArranged marriagezSri Lanka. 0aMarriagezSri Lanka. 0aSocial changezSri Lanka. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aMarriage, gender, Sinhala-Buddhist, Sri Lanka, modern subjectivities, politics of marriage, gendered selves, Sinhala, divorce, failed marriages, Abeyasekera, kinship, family, gender identity, modernity, middle-class, feminist, Buddhist, morality, social mobility, intergenerational conflict, modern, becoming modern, Kimberly, Guinta, love, global, desire, North India, social structures, culture, sexuality, material culture, political economy, marriage in North India, sexual consent, consensual relationships, legal subjectivity, marital patterns, arranged marriages, anthropology, Indian state, feminism, legal anthropology, aspiration.1 aBerta, Péter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021 Englishz978311075418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021z9783110753967oZDB-23-DSL08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073913840uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197881034140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978810341423Coveruhttps://www.degruyt